{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1772048153,"nonce":"7jphXRyl026RJ3nmXy1IicNhXaI=","message":"[GitHub comment by i-m-mll on 2026-02-05T03:35:16Z]\n\n## Architectural context update\n\nThe `_WhereStrConstructor` tracer approach effectively solves the serialization/hashing problem for where-functions. However, now that feedbax has an eager graph system with string-based node/port addressing, there's a broader architectural question:\n\n- **Graph level**: Nodes addressed by string keys (`graph.nodes[\"encoder\"]`), wires reference string ports\n- **Parameter level**: Still uses where-functions for `eqx.tree_at` surgeries\n\nIs this separation intentional (graph topology vs. internal parameter access), or should there eventually be a unified addressing scheme? See also #38 (Penzai-like selectors) which might provide a more integrated approach.\n\nThe tracer can bridge both worlds (lambdas in code → strings for serialization/UI → back to lambdas), so one answer is: \"where-functions are fine for code ergonomics, with the tracer as the interchange format.\"\n\nAnother consideration: if the UI allows users to select model parts visually, the UI becomes the source of truth for paths — no manual where-function writing, no drift between code and structure.\n\n---\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.5 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}